<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-205-392 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 460 653</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  March 4 1991 v5 n6 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NASA sends space station back to the drawing board.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mercier, Ann M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>NASA will redesign its space station so that it is less expensive,smaller, and more modular in the wake of decreased funding andproject delays.andP;  The space station will also use simpler and fewercomputers, the architecture of its data management system has alsobeen simplified.andP;  NASA expects to deliver plans for the new spacestation to Congress in Mar 1991.andP;  The new space station is nowbudgeted at $16 billion.andP;  The changes will affect NASA'sagreements with its prime contractors for the space station, suchas McDonnell Douglas Space Systems Co, Boeing Aerospace Co, andRocketdyne Division, Rockwell International, but NASA says thatthe changes were prenegotiated into the contracts.andP;  The new spacestation will begin operation with a 50M-bps data link, rather thanthe 300M-bps link that was originally planned, and detachedpayloads will be indefinitely deferred.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Space CraftSpace ExplorationCost ReductionProject ManagementUnited States. National Aeronautics and Space AdministrationDesignModularity.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>